2024 Spatial Hackathon Vignette: Core Functionality

Set-up

Getting nearest neighbours

Load the Xenium Breast Cancer dataset (Replicate 1).

data_dir = 'C:/Users/kwaje/Downloads/HACKATHON/'

A quick plot to see distribution of cell types in space. Using 2D histograms / hex is typically faster than plotting individual spots in space (thus we avoid geom_point).

Below, we present our function for getting nearest neighbours per cell. This is most rapidly obtained using Delaunay triangulation (DT) - but we have also implemented a slower version using Euclidean distance cutoffs. Below, we get DT-derived 1st-3rd order neighbours to show functionality - but getting the first order neighbours is sufficient for this dataset. Note that the set of 3rd order neighbours will contain both 1st and 2nd order neighbours, as well as new neighbours.

Verbose is set to TRUE as default to log progress.

nndf <- getNNMatrix(
  x = adf$x_centroid,
  y = adf$y_centroid,
  cell_label = adf$cluster,
  delaunayTriangulationDistanceThreshold = 20,
  delaunayNNDegrees = c(1:3),
  euclideanDistances = NULL,
  verbose = T
  )

What is returned is a matrix of n cells x (cell types x number of degrees or thresholds requested). In this dataset, we have 20 cell types and 167780 cells. Since the above requests to return 1st-3rd order neighbours, we have a matrix of 167780 rows and (20 x 3) columns.

The function removes several edges: (1) convex hull, (2) edges > chosen distance. The default distance is 20 units (depends on what units are used in the x/y coordinate system), but users can reduce the distance as needed. One quick way of examining suitable distances is to sample random coordinates and see the distribution distances of the top n closest neighbours.

set.seed(12345)
coords <- adf$x_centroid + adf$y_centroid * 1i
refs <- sample(coords, size = 1000, replace = F)
dists <- sapply(refs, function(f){ 
  d <- Mod(coords - f)
  d <- d[d>0]
  d <- sort(d, decreasing = F)
  d <- d[1:10]
  })
ggplot(data.frame('val' = as.vector(dists))) +
  geom_histogram(aes(x=val), fill='black', bins=200) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 20) +
  scale_x_log10() + xlab('Nearest 10 distances for 1000 samples') +
  ggtitle(paste0('Median = ', round(median(dists), digits=2)))

Permutation testing

Across the entire tissue, we might ask how often any two cell types are clustered together. Note that ‘clustered together’ can have varying meanings: e.g. we could be talking about neighbours within 10 units of Euclidean distance, or 20 units etc.

One quick way to test for significance is to use a permutation test. Below is an example to see which cell types are significantly co-localising with B cells (specifically, how often a B cell is a first order neighbour of any other cell type). We will use a one-tailed (greater) permuation test here.

ref_cell_type = paste(limma::strsplit2(colnames(nndf)[1], '_')[,-1], collapse='_')
print(ref_cell_type)
[1] "B_Cells"
nPerms = 1000
cell_labels <- adf$cluster

obs <- by(nndf[,1], cell_labels, sum)
obs <- setNames(as.numeric(obs), names(obs))

set.seed(12345)
nulldist <- list()
for(px in 1:nPerms){
  null_labs <- sample(cell_labels, size = length(cell_labels), replace = F)
  expx <- by(nndf[,1], null_labs, sum)
  expx <- setNames(as.numeric(expx), names(expx))
  nulldist[[px]] <- expx
  }
nulldist <- do.call(cbind, nulldist)
mean_exp <- rowMeans(nulldist)
sd_exp <- apply(nulldist, 1, sd)
pvals <- sapply(1:nrow(nulldist), function(j){
    pval = 1 - sum( obs[j] < nulldist[j,]) / nPerms
    pval = 1 - pval
    return(pval)
    })

Here, the null distributions (black) do reasonably follow a normal distribution (red). If desired, Z-scoring can be used to calculate p values - should a parametric test be desired. However, approximation to normality cannot always be guaranteed. In such cases, empirically obtained p values are more reliable (though at the cost of p values having a floor of 1 / nPerms).

set.seed(12345)
gaussian_pred <- do.call(rbind, setNames(lapply(1:nrow(nulldist), function(i){
  val <- rnorm( nPerms, mean = mean(nulldist[i,]), sd = sd(nulldist[i,]) )
  return(val)
}), rownames(nulldist)))
ggplot() +
  geom_density(data = reshape2::melt(gaussian_pred), aes(value), colour='red') +
  geom_density(data = reshape2::melt(nulldist), aes(value), colour='black') +
  theme_minimal(base_size=10) +
  facet_wrap(~Var1, scales='free') +
  ggtitle('Null distributions')

We see below that immune cells are those significantly clustering with B cells.

print(
  data.frame(
  'OBS' = obs,
  'OBS PERCENT' = round(100 * obs / sum(obs), digits=2), 
  'MEAN EXP' = mean_exp,
  'SD EXP' = sd_exp,
  'Z' = (obs - mean_exp)/sd_exp,
  'PVAL' = pvals,
  'SIG' = c('***', '**', '*', '.', '')[as.integer(cut(pvals, c(1, 0.1, 0.05, 0.01, 0.001, -1)))]
  )  
)

We have written a function to return the above table quickly.

While the above permutation test is useful for a global look at the tissue, there may be regions of the tissue that have different abundance profiles than others. To examine that further, we implemented a number of neighbourhood enrichment approaches (next section).

Neighbourhood enrichment

Given a neighbourhood matrix, users may want to identify anatomically distinct regions. This is fundamentally a latent factor identification problem. We offer several ways to do this:

  1. (Current default) Non-negative Matrix Factorisation (NMF)
  2. (Requires Python) Correlation Explanation (CorEx)
  3. (In progress) Hidden Markov Model (HMM)

NMF

For NMF, we use a very fast implementation using the RcppML package (a C++ implementation of the Kim and Park 2007 algorithm). To identify suitable number of factors, one quick way is to estimate using the number of Principle Components used to explain X% of variance.

As input we use log10-transformed n neighbours for convenience. Getting neighbours at multiple resolutions is also assumed to be advantageous for this purpose; hence we use the whole NN matrix (across multiple degrees).

npcs = 40
pca <- irlba::prcomp_irlba(log10(1+nndf), n = npcs)
Warning: You're computing too large a percentage of total singular values, use a standard svd instead.
par(mfrow=c(2,1))
plot( y = 100 * (pca$sdev^2) / sum(pca$sdev^2),
      x = 1:npcs, ylab = 'VarEx (%)', xlab = 'nPCs')
plot( y = cumsum(100 * (pca$sdev^2) / sum(pca$sdev^2)),
      x = 1:npcs, ylab = 'Cum VarEx (%)', xlab = 'nPCs')
par(mfrow=c(1,1))

Choice of k is otherwise arbitrary. One approach is maybe to pick a high value of k and then merge clusters together afterwards.

latent_factors <- getNNLatentFactors(
  log10(1+nndf),
  method = 'nmf',
  k = 9,
  seed = 12345
)

w <- latent_factors$CELL_LOADINGS
if(!all(colnames(w) %in% colnames(adf))){
  adf <- cbind(adf, w)

ggplot( reshape2::melt(adf, measure.vars=colnames(w))) +
  stat_summary_hex(aes(x=x_centroid, y=y_centroid, z=value), fun = mean, bins=100) +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(option='turbo') +

And below are the contribution of each feature to each NMF factor. We have split the loadings per degree (e.g. 1st degree neighbours = 1, 2nd degree neighbours (inclusive of 1) = 2 etc). Factor 3 is our immunological niche and confirmed by enrichment of lymphocytes. Factor 2, our invasive tumour etc. Note how results are relatively robust across degrees - suggesting that the same factors would have likely been obtained even if degree was restricted to 1 (instead of ranging 1-3).

h <- latent_factors$FEATURE_LOADINGS
tmp <- reshape2::melt(
  data.frame(h, 'Factor' = 1:nrow(h), check.names = F), 
  id.vars = c('Factor')
  )
tmp$METHOD <- limma::strsplit2(tmp$variable, '_')[,1]
tmp$DEGREE <- as.integer(gsub('^\\D+', '', tmp$METHOD))
tmp$CT <- substr(tmp$variable, nchar(tmp$METHOD) + 2, nchar(as.character(tmp$variable)))

ggplot(tmp) +
  geom_point(aes(x=Factor, y=CT, size = value, colour=value)) +
  scale_colour_viridis_c(option='turbo') +
  theme_minimal(base_size=14) +
  facet_wrap(~DEGREE, nrow=1) +
  ylab('')

Users can evaluate how well their NMF factor identification has worked by examining how redundant factor loadings are. This can be quickly obtained via correlation. Below, one could suggest clustering NMF3 (lymphocyte) and NMF5 (macrophage 1) into a single factor; or keep them separate if a correlation of 0.34 is unconvincingly similar.

pheatmap(
  cor(w), display_numbers = T
)

CorEx

CorEx is another matrix factorisation approach that uses multivariate mutual information. It is used typically in the field of topic modelling, but we have found it useful for sparse data. CorEx takes a binary (0/1) matrix and identifies groups of features that can be grouped into a latent factor. Its current implementation assumes that feature contribution per latent factor is non-overlapping (a choice borne of speed of implementation, rather than accuracy). It is thus probably most advantageous in scenarios where (1) there are a lot of cell type clusters (so that grouping these clusters into latent factors is meaningful), (2) very few cells per cell type as neighbours (amenable to binarisation).

Currently, anchoring is not supported using our function; but users can directly interface with the CorEx module for custom coding.

latent_factors <- getNNLatentFactors(
  nndf,
  method = 'corex',
  k = 9,
  seed = 12345
)

As before, we can see cell loadings in space. Also note that the default w matrix is in log probabilities, and can be exponentiated.

w <- latent_factors$CELL_LOADINGS
if(!all(colnames(w) %in% colnames(adf))){
  adf <- cbind(adf, w)
}

ggplot( reshape2::melt(adf, measure.vars=colnames(w))) +
  stat_summary_hex(aes(x=x_centroid, y=y_centroid, z=exp(value)), fun = mean, bins=100) +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(option='turbo') +
  facet_wrap(~variable, nrow = 3) +
  theme_void(base_size = 20)

Note that CorEx’s feature loadings matrix is binary (0/1) - to reflect assignment of a feature to one of the n factors.

h <- latent_factors$FEATURE_LOADINGS
tmp <- reshape2::melt(
  data.frame(h, 'Factor' = 1:nrow(h), check.names = F), 
  id.vars = c('Factor')
  )
tmp$METHOD <- limma::strsplit2(tmp$variable, '_')[,1]
tmp$DEGREE <- as.integer(gsub('^\\D+', '', tmp$METHOD))
tmp$CT <- substr(tmp$variable, nchar(tmp$METHOD) + 2, nchar(as.character(tmp$variable)))

ggplot(tmp) +
  geom_point(aes(x=Factor, y=CT, size = value, colour=value)) +
  scale_colour_viridis_c(option='turbo') +
  theme_minimal(base_size=14) +
  facet_wrap(~DEGREE, nrow=1) +
  ylab('')

As before, we can ask if any clusters are redundant.

pheatmap(
  cor(exp(w)), display_numbers = T
